  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC COVID-19 Global Appeal Asia Region</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC is present in &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.drc.ngo/where-we-work/asia&quot;&gt;3 countries&lt;/a&gt; in the Asia Region and has implemented Covid-19 specific activities in all three of them: &lt;i&gt; Afghanistan, Bangladesh &amp; Myanmar &lt;/i&gt;. &lt;br&gt; The operations work in largely different scenarios, with Bangladesh and Myanmar connected through the Rohingya displacement axis. &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt; &lt;b&gt; Community Engagement/AVR &amp; WASH &lt;/b&gt; are the sectors with the highest ammount of targeted people in this region.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&lt;b&gt; In Bangladesh &lt;/b&gt; DRC is one of the largest site managers in the Rohingya refugee camps. DRC intends to build structures to aid the COVID-19 response, such as &lt;b&gt; isolation shelters, disinfection areas and hand-washing stations &lt;/b&gt;, as well as provide materials to households to enable them to isolate part of their shelter should a household member fall ill. DRC will also &lt;b&gt; train refugees and members of host communities to produce personal protective equipment &lt;/b&gt; and provide &lt;b&gt; cash for work &lt;/b&gt; opportunities to help maintain household incomes. In response to increased rates of GBV and child protection issues, DRC will provide &lt;b&gt; case management &lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt; support to access health and other services &lt;/b&gt;. &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt; &lt;b&gt; In Myanmar &lt;/b&gt; DRC manages eight IDP camps and is seeking to improve &lt;b&gt; WASH infrastructure &lt;/b&gt; by rehabilitating and building new sanitation and handwashing stations. Field-based staff have been engaging with communities within the camps to &lt;b&gt; promote hygiene practices &lt;/b&gt; . &lt;b&gt; Protection monitoring and case management &lt;/b&gt; of GBV and child protection cases is continuing where feasible. In locations where IDPs can access markets, DRC will provide vulnerable households with &lt;b&gt; cash to cover basic needs. &lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt; &lt;b&gt; In Afghanistan &lt;/b&gt; DRC will address &lt;b&gt; COVID-19 risks in congested IDP camps &lt;/b&gt; where livelihoods are affected by the close-down of markets and move-ment restrictions focusing on the provision of &lt;b&gt; NFI kits including hygiene kits; multipurpose cash assistance; vulnerability screening, referral services, and the distribution of protection kits &lt;/b&gt;.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&lt;b&gt; In Myanmar &lt;/b&gt; DRC response targets vulnerable IDPs in camps and IDP sites and conflict-affected people in Rakhine, meeting protection needs through psychosocial support, prevention of gender-based violence, and child protection. Target groups include female headed households, child-headed households, households with chronically ill people, households with people living with disabilities, and those where women breastfeed or are headed by old people. &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt; &lt;b&gt; In Bangladesh &lt;/b&gt; DRC targets primarily people living in the Rohingya Refugee camps. DRC has also identified the host communities, including female-headed households, households with pregnant and lactating mothers, households with people living with disabilities, and low-income earners such as day labourers as vulnerable groups. &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt; &lt;b&gt; In Afghanistan &lt;/b&gt; , the DRC programme puts an emphasis of providing COVID-19 specific risk education for returnees, IDPs, and vulnerable host communities, together with in-kind distributions.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">DRC has received new funding from donors for it&apos;s COVID-19 response. At the same time, many donors have permitted us to re-programme existing grants for our COVID-19 specific work. While for now we are only reporting the financial volume of the new COVID-19 specific grants, we will also report on our re-programmed funds as soon as this information becomes available to us. &lt;br&gt; &lt;br&gt; &lt;b&gt; The OECD DAC CRS Purpose Codes &lt;/b&gt; used to describe this activity refers to the amount of people reached, seen as a percentage of all single instances of beneficiaries reached. This means that it can include double counting, if single individuals have been counted multiple times for different sectors.</narrative>
  </description>
